			    <HR color=#000000 SIZE=-1>
			  	certifiedgeek;<br />
<br />
Planet rearranging (digging into the core to put good planets there) is done all the time by the successful councils, even OOA teaches it to the new players.  So getting rid of the planet destruction probably only hurts the uncoordinated councils full of new players that haven't learned all of the tricks of the trade yet.<br />
<br />
As for commerce, please keep in mind that commerce is not just with other members of your council.  You also establish commerce routes with players from other councils that your council is allied or pacted with.  As for the amount of PP you get from commerce, it is a percentage of the PP produced on the planets you are trading with (up to three per planet).  So it has nothing to do with how many players are in the council (well, it isn't limited by that).  For instance, if you are in a council of 40 new players that have nothing but a bunch of planets with 70% bases on them, you will not do as well as you might in a council with 3 veteran players that have cores of URs with 100% factories.  Keep these things in mind when determining which councils to accept alliances or pacts with.  If they are a puny council with little hope of gaining high producing planets, simply reject the offer and suggest it be a verbal alliance (other than trade, there isn't any real game reason to be allied with other councils anyway).  Most players have relationships with other players in the game that supercede any council relationships (there are some players I won't attack, nor will they attack me, even if our councils are at war - I let my council leaders know of these situations as they arise).			   <P align=right></P>
